<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>House of Commons Transport Committee</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">Written evidence from</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> Dr David Metz, University College London (SRN 006)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Su</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">mmary</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.33pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">The benefits of the Government’s proposed investment in the strategic road network are not well defined in prospect and are uncertain in outcome.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.33pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">Much of the traffic on the most heavily used part of the network is local, rather than long distance.</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> Adding additional carriageway tends to foster more local traffic.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.33pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">There is no strategic context for the proposed roads programme.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.33pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">Future travel demand will be driven by demographic factors, particularly population growth</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">, not by income growth. </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">The Departm</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">ent for Transport’s National Tran</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">sport Model is</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> misleading</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> in its traffic projections</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.33pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">The most beneficial investment in the strategic road network would be in predictive journey time information </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">to allow road users to</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> mitigate congestion.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.33pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">The Highways Age</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">ncy is a twentieth century organisation that needs to transition to the era of digital technologies.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">How will the policies set out in the Government’s “Action for Roads” command paper improve the strategic road network for all road users, whilst also impr</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">oving the environment?</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 6pt 14.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">The benefits of the proposed investment to improve the strategic road network are not well defined in the command paper</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">. </span><a name="_ednref1"></a><a href="#_edn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">It seems to be implicit that the investment would reduce congestion. However, it has long been recognised tha</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">t ‘we cannot build our way out of congestion’, a consideration not addressed in the paper. Moreover, there is no mention of the scope for dema</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">nd management as an approach to capacity constraints at times of peak usage.</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 6pt 14.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">The command paper states that particular projects within the investment programme will proceed ‘subject to value for money and deliverability.’ Value for money has conventionally meant achieving a suitably high benefit-to-cost ratio, where the bulk of the </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">benefits are </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">assumed to be travel time savings. However, average travel time has remained at </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">about </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">an hour a day for at least the past 40 years, according to the National Travel Survey. </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">Time savings are therefore transient. </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">long run </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">benefits of investm</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">ent in the transport system are taken in the form of longer trips at higher speed</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">, which allow more access, opportunities and choice. The mechanism</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> to generate </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">economic </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">benefits</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> is that public investment in </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">transport</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> system</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">makes land more accessible</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> which prompts the private sector to invest</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> profitably</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> in commercial and residential property, which</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> in turn</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> creates new </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">jobs</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> and homes. Thus East London is undergoing regeneration based on rail investment in Docklands and beyond. </span></li><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 6pt 14.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">The construction of the </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">strategic road network had a major impact </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">on</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> land use, for instance as seen in the consolidation of retail supply chains</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">into </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">central warehousing from which the bulk of outlets can be supplied out and back within the working day, thus saving inventory and </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">estate costs. However, </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">now we have</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> a mature network, few </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">further such efficiency gains ar</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">e possible</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">, and what is proposed in the command paper seems likely to have limited impact.</span></li><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 14.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">The Government plans to widen busy motorways on the periphery of conurbation</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">s, where there is a lot of </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">traffic</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">. However, experience is that such new road capacity fills up pretty quickly with extra traffic—and congestion is restored to what it was. Consider the M25 orbital motorway around London. About half of the traffic is long </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">distance, for instance from south coast ports to the Midlands avoiding central London</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> (in respect of which there is a lack of evidence of long run growth)</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">. The other half is local traffic, people travelling to work and making other trips, taking advantage </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">of a segment of the motorway to speed their journeys. Road widening at first allows higher speeds at peak hours and so permits people to travel a bit further for more choice of jobs</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">homes</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">, shopping etc</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">. As a result, pressures arise to develop land in or n</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">ear the Green Belt around Londo</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">n for housing or commercial use.</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> The extra distances travelled by car to and from both existing and new developments result additional traffic—known as ‘induced traffic’, the consequence of the extra capacity—which results in</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> additional carbon and other emissions, noise and accidents, with no congestion reduction in the long run on account of the extra traffic. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 14.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">Widening the M25 and similar sections of busy motorway in effect amounts to enlarging the capacity of a local </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">distributor road in the neighbourhood of a conurbation. This permits local property development at the cost of greater traffic volumes, while having little impact on the performance of long distance traffic. We now have a mature road network, with few plan</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">s for any wholly new roads. Adding an additional lane at very considerable expense </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">seems</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> poor value, as are the schemes for ‘managed motorways’ that involve use of the hard shoulders as an additional traffic lane under congested condition, subject to reduc</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">ed speed limits. The benefits of road improvements are now very </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">modest. A</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">n evaluation of 58 major schemes recently implemented by the Highw</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">ays Agency</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> found time savings to road users at peak usage of only three minutes on average. The resulting long run ch</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">anges to land use would be small and diffuse.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 6pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">How does the Government’s policy for roads link with planning for other transport modes?</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 6pt 14.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">The Government has no overall vision for the strategic development of the transport sector</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">. There is an intention to publish a National Policy Statement for Transport Networks (including rail and roads), under the framework of the planning Act 2008, but no draft has yet been issued for consultation. </span></li><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 6pt 14.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">For all travel modes (other than internation</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">al aviation), </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">per capita </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">average travel time, journey number and distance travelled have been essentially unchanged since the mid-1990. This should be the basis of a business-as-usual planning central case. Future growth in travel demand will be driven by </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">demographic factors.</span></li><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 6pt 14.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">Any national policy statement for transport would need to recognise the significant popul</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">ation growth expected</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> and its implications for future travel demand. </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">The population of England is projected to increase by a substantial 8.6% betw</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">een 2011 and 2021. </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">Housing the additional inhabitants on greenfield sites on the edge of existing settlements would result in increased car ownership and use, whereas accommodating them in existing urban areas at higher density, in brownfield developments </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">or more intensive use of extant property, would increase demand for public transport. London has a growing population that is being accommodated at higher density, where car use is constrained by road capacity, and all the increase in travel demand is bein</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">g met by investment in public transport. Londoners not owning cars are a main source of growth of interurban rail travel.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 6pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">How reliable is the Government’s forecast for growth in demand for the strategic road network? How should the Government deal with unc</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">ertainty in its forecast?</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 6pt 14.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">The Department for Transport’s latest Road Transport Forecasts project substantial traffic growth on the strategic road network</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">, based on the output of the National Transport Model—car traffic increase by 2040 of 43% on the Centr</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">al Case. </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">However, the Model does not distinguish between long distance and local traffic growth on the strategic road network. It is likely that the bulk of </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">any</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> projected growth </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">would be</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> local traffic, rather than the long distance traffic for which the ne</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">twork is intended.</span></li><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 6pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">he Model projects an increase in London car traffic of 36%, which is very hard to </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">understand</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">, given that car traffic in London has hardly changed over the past twenty yea</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">rs. The Model appears to be mis-</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">specified as regards road capacity in London, and probably </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">in </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">other large urban areas.</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 6pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">The National Travel Survey shows that average distance travelled by all modes (other than international air travel) has remained at about 7,000 miles per person per yea</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">r since the mid-1990</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">s. 80% of this distance is travelled by car, hence the observed cessation of per capita growth of car us in Britain, as well as in most developed countries. Th</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">is is the phenomenon known as ‘Peak C</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">ar’. The his</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">toric relation between growt</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">h of</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> incomes and growth of travel demand no longer applies. In future, travel demand will depend on demographic factors—population growth, location of extra inhabitants, increasing longevity (which is inducing urban younger people to defer car ownership) a</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">nd an ageing population.</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 6pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">The National Transport Model seems not to have incorporated </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">these emerging changes in travel behaviour. As with all econometric models, it is essentially backward looking, </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">making projections</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> into the future based on past experienc</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">e of the influence of a few parameters such as GDP growth, population growth and oil prices. Moreover, this Model is not open to external scrutiny and use, unlike the T</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">reasury’s model of the economy or DECC</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">’s</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> greenhouse gas emissions model.</span></li><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 6pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">There is inevit</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">able uncertainty in any projection. A useful approach is to adopt scenarios, rather than a Central Case with sensitivities. One scenario might correspond to the Department’s Central Case. Another might reflect </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">the Peak Car perspective. Such an approach wou</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">ld help identify investment strategies that would be most robust to </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">future uncertainty.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 6pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">How can we improve the reliability and efficiency of travel on the strategic road network? What impact will new technology have?</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 6pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">Findings from surveys of road users ind</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">icate that the</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">ir</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> main concern arising from congestion is uncertainty of journey time, and the</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">ir</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> main response is to vary departure time. There are two kinds of user of the strategic road network: those who have to be at their destination at a particular ti</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">me, for instance to get to work or a meeting; and those who are flexible, for example when </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">driving to shops</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> or</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> leisure activities. Both </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">could</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> benefit from predictive information about journey times, the former to choose the optimum departure time, the latter to avoid traffic</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">congestion— a ‘win-win’ situation since the flexible drivers minimises their own journey time uncertainty while, by absen</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">ting themselves, lessening that of the inflexible drivers.</span></li><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 6pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">The efficient road freight operators are typically contracted to deliver to customers’ premises in tight time slots, for instance 30 min at supermarkets. This performance they can achieve because t</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">hey have a good knowledge of traffic on the road network and of the location of each vehicle in the fleet. Estimates of the ‘cost of congestion’ of</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> between £8bn and £30bn a year </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">put abou</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">t by trade association</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">s take no account of such efficiency and are acc</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">ordingly quite misleading.</span></li><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 6pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">Building on the experience of the road freight operators, the most useful application of digital technologies to improving the efficiency of the strategic road network would be to make generally available predictive journey time </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">information for direct routes. At present Satnav devices and Internet-based</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">sources </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">offer optimal routes with estimated journey times based on historic traffic conditions or, in some cases, real time traffic data. There are examples also of provision of pr</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">edictive traffic information</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">. It would be desirable for </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">the Highways Agency actively</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> to promulgate information about pr</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">edictive journey time</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">s, to improve network efficiency. There is also scope for providing information about alternative routes to avoid co</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">ngestion, but because the capacity of these is limited, it would be sensible levy a charge, set to constrain usage to a level consistent with capacity. Such a subscription service would naturally be for private sector service providers.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 6pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">What mechanisms are</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt"> there for Government to increase investment in strategic roads and attract new investors? Are there good examples from other countries that could be applied in the UK? </span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 6pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">As discussed above, the case for investment in additional strategic road capacity is n</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">ot well established, which means that a business case to attract new investors would be problematic. Developing such a prospectus would, however, be a useful undertaking in that it wo</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">uld require a clear exposition of the expected benefits and cash flows.</span></li><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">A</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">ustralian experience of private sector investment in roads is relevant. Since 2005 a number of Australian toll roads have failed to meet their traffic forecasts leading to project distress and in some cases default. Equity providers have lost their investm</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">ent and distressed debt is trading at </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">discounts of up t</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">o 70 per cent. T</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">he problem is that traffic forecasts for </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">these</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> toll roads have been </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">boosted</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> to win concessions and have been used as part of a sales pitch to attract investors</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> </span><a name="_ednref2"></a><a href="#_edn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 6pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">How should the </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">Highways Agency be reformed to make it “the world’s leading highway operator”? What roles should Government and the private sector play to ensure better management of the strategic road network?</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 6pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">The Highways Agency is a very cautious organisation </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">that</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> has </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">a strong preference for investment in civil engineering technology. Its interest in the application of demand management techniques to achieve better network performance is </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">very </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">limited. Provision of traffic information via </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">its</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> website is not </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">user-friendly</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">. The</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> Agency’s</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> new pl</span><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">anning approach of route-based strategies disregards entirely the opportunities for providing information that would influence how road users use the network. In short, the Highways Agency is a twentieth-century organisation </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">that</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> needs</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> to </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">move into the twenty-first century in which digital innovation will be much more cost-effect</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">ive in achieving its objectives than pouring concrete or rolling tarmac.</span></li><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 6pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">Given </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">from </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">where it starts, it may not be sensible for the Agency to build an in-house </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">digital capability. Rather, it should aim to partner with private sector innovators to develop approaches to network management, demand management and driver information that improve </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">both </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">operational efficiency and road user benefits.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 6pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">15 October 2013</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 6pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">Dr David Metz, visiting professor, Centre for Transport Studies, University College London, formerly Chief Scientist, Department for Transport. </span><a name="_ednref3"></a><a href="#_edn3">[3]</a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_edn1"></a><a href="#_ednref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">I</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> offer no comment on proposed expenditure on maintenance.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_edn2"></a><a href="#_ednref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> </span><a href="http://www.robbain.com/Toll%20Roads.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.robbain.com/Toll Roads.pdf</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_edn3"></a><a href="#_ednref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">This evidence is based on analysis carried out by the author, to be </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">summarised</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> in a forthcoming book </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Peak Car – the future of travel</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">. Published papers can be found at www.davidmetz.org</span></p></body></html>